history.content:
54 should be a good chunk of it. 

There might be some stuff you have to review without 16B, but if you're not averse to putting a little extra work, I'm sure you can make it work. I doubt 110 is needed at all.

children.subject: I took 20 and 40 rather than 16ab, but from what I understand, 16b isn't a math class like 110 or 127. Unless 127 uses examples from electrical engineering, I'm not sure why you'd need circuits or signals at all. For 16b without 16a, you'd ideally need to understand basic circuits (KCL, KVL, nodal and mesh methods, op-amps) in addition to basic linear algebra. Physics 7b would likely help, but 110 likely wouldn't be of any use. Maybe 185 would help, because phasor analysis of circuits is an application of complex analysis (or so I've heard) but I'm not sure if 110 covers any of that.

To the person who wrote the student reply, thanks! I'm taking M110 because I want to learn that material and it satisfies a requirement for one of my majors. I mentioned it here because I was curious if it would help supplant some of the pre-req material from 16a/b. 

So if I understand you correctly, I should be able to take EE127 without 16A/B, correct? And what about taking 16B without taking 16A?

history.content:
I want to take EE127, which has EE16A and B as pre-req's. I took a different class that satisfies the requirement of taking EE16A already, but it was a long time ago. I left school to work for a few years, so assume that it was long ago enough that I don't remember any of the content. 

I have taken Math 54 (also a while ago, but much more recently than when I took the EE16A equivalent), and plan to take Math 110 this summer. 

Would I be OK jumping into EE16B in the Fall, straight after taking Math 110? Is there any overlap between 16A and Math 110? 

And would I be able to do well in EE127 with taking Math 110 + EE16B as pre-req's for EE127?
